#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""pr-finalize — post a curated REVIEW.md to GitHub as one review object.

Companion to the `pr-review` script. pr-review prepares a PR and runs the
sandboxed review that writes REVIEW.md; a human curates it (checks the box on
each finding worth posting); pr-finalize posts the result. It takes no
arguments — the PR and the reviewed head come from the preparation snapshot
(.pr-review/state.json), never from REVIEW.md's frontmatter. REVIEW.md's *body*
is parsed for the curation state; the closed ### grammar makes that a machine's
job, so no model sits in the posting path.

Runs unsandboxed: it needs the network (a live head check and the POST) and
reads local files plus gh. The only external tool is gh — already required by
pr-review. JSON is built with the standard library, so there is no jq
dependency (gh embeds jq for its own output for the same reason standalone jq
can't be assumed present).

Routing is by SECTION ORDINAL, not heading text. A human may relabel a heading,
but the first three ## sections are Problems, Observations, Pre-existing, in
that order, and the empty-sections rule keeps the mapping stable:

  - sections 1 & 2: a located finding posts as an inline comment, and MUST land
    in the diff or the single review object would 422. An out-of-diff finding
    here is a misfiled pre-existing one or a stale anchor, and is refused — not
    silently rerouted. A locationless finding folds into the PR-level body
    under its (verbatim) heading label.
  - section 3: every finding folds, carrying a blob permalink when it is located.

Code links are authored one way throughout REVIEW.md — the VS Code-relative
](./path#line) grammar a ### heading already uses — so the same link is
navigable in the local checkout during curation whether it sits in a heading or
in prose. Prose and the body post to GitHub verbatim, where a relative link is
dead, so linkify_prose rewrites each to a blob permalink at post time (only the
posted copy; REVIEW.md on disk stays relative). In prose the #line fragment is
optional — a fragmentless ./path names the file and permalinks to it — because
only a ### heading's link is a comment anchor, and an anchor needs a line. A
fragment that is not a bare line number (./path#L52) is refused by name.

The review's verdict follows from curation alone: with no checked finding it is
posted as an APPROVE; with any checked finding — in any of the three sections,
since the checkbox (not the section) is the blocking signal — it is a
REQUEST_CHANGES. COMMENT is not used: GitHub drops a PR out of "review
requested" the moment any review lands, regardless of event, so a non-committal
COMMENT would only deny the author a next-step signal. An empty body is fine:
GitHub requires a REQUEST_CHANGES review to carry a body OR comments (verified
empirically; the docs' "body is required" wording overstates it), and every
REQUEST_CHANGES this tool sends carries one or the other by construction.

No inline comment is ever out-of-diff, so the all-or-nothing post is safe by
construction. The hard refusals are a moved PR head, an already-posted
preparation, and a pending review carrying replies or file-level comments (see
below).

The curator's own pending GitHub review (the "Start a review" flow) would 422
that POST — GitHub allows one pending review per user per PR. Instead of
failing, pr-finalize detects it and offers to fold it in: its comments join
the payload verbatim (anchors pass through untouched, LEFT-side and multi-line
included — GitHub anchored them to the diff by construction, so they need no
in-diff lint), its draft body, if any, lands at the end of the review body
after a ---, and the pending review is deleted from GitHub just before the
POST. Everything fetched is persisted to .pr-review-run/pending-import.json
first — a recovery artifact, never an input: the ordering is fetch → persist →
confirm → delete → post, so if the POST fails after the delete, the file holds
the only surviving copy. An imported comment is a human-authored finding, so
it forces REQUEST_CHANGES like a checked one. There is no "post without
importing" — the POST cannot succeed while the pending review exists — so the
choices are import or abort (submit or discard on github.com, then re-run).
Two shapes are refused by name: replies (the create-review comments array
cannot express in_reply_to, and posting them separately would break the
all-or-nothing post) and file-level comments (no line anchor; payload support
unconfirmed).

On success REVIEW.md is kept — unchecked findings survive for a follow-up — and
a posted.md marker in the run directory closes the preparation, refusing a
second post here and a re-run from pr-review. Re-prepare to reopen.

Usage:  pr-finalize            post the prepared PR
        pr-finalize --dry-run  parse, route and print the payload; post nothing
"""

from __future__ import annotations

import json
import shutil
import subprocess
import sys
from pathlib import Path
from typing import NoReturn

# The grammar, model and linter live in pr_review_lint.py beside this script.
# resolve() follows the ~/.local/bin symlink pr-install creates back to the
# real bin dir, where pr-install copies the module alongside this file, so the
# import works whether pr-finalize runs in place or through that symlink.
sys.path.insert(0, str(Path(__file__).resolve().parent))
from pr_review_lint import (  # noqa: E402
    Problem, Section, parse_review, parse_diff_ranges, lint, bail_on_problems,
    PROSE_LINK, TEXT_END_L,
)

PROG = "pr-finalize"
STATE_DIR = Path(".pr-review")
RUN_DIR = Path(".pr-review-run")
REVIEW = Path("REVIEW.md")
POSTED_MD = RUN_DIR / "posted.md"
POSTED_JSON = RUN_DIR / "posted.json"
PENDING_IMPORT = RUN_DIR / "pending-import.json"


def die(msg: str) -> NoReturn:
    print(f"{PROG}: {msg}", file=sys.stderr)
    raise SystemExit(1)


# --- shelling out to git/gh ---------------------------------------------------

def _run(*args: str, stdin: str | None = None) -> subprocess.CompletedProcess:
    return subprocess.run(args, input=stdin, text=True, capture_output=True)


def git(*args: str, what: str) -> str:
    p = _run("git", *args)
    if p.returncode != 0:
        die(f"{what} failed: {p.stderr.strip() or 'git error'}")
    return p.stdout.strip()


def gh(*args: str, what: str, stdin: str | None = None) -> str:
    p = _run("gh", *args, stdin=stdin)
    if p.returncode != 0:
        die(f"{what} failed: {p.stderr.strip() or 'gh error'}")
    return p.stdout


def gh_api_list(path: str, what: str) -> list[dict]:
    """GET a paginated array endpoint as one list. `--paginate` alone would
    concatenate the pages' arrays into invalid JSON, so each element is
    flattened to one raw JSON line instead (gh prints jq string results raw)."""
    out = gh("api", "--paginate", path, "--jq", ".[] | @json", what=what)
    return [json.loads(line) for line in out.splitlines() if line.strip()]


# --- routing and assembly -----------------------------------------------------

def permalink(nwo: str, head: str, path: str,
              start: int | None = None, end: int | None = None) -> str:
    """A blob permalink at the reviewed head, line-pinned when given a start.

    Without a start it names the file as a whole, which GitHub serves fine — the
    line fragment is only compulsory where a link becomes a comment ANCHOR."""
    url = f"https://github.com/{nwo}/blob/{head}/{path}"
    if start is None:
        return url
    frag = f"L{start}" + (f"-L{end}" if end and end > start else "")
    return f"{url}#{frag}"


def linkify_prose(text: str, nwo: str, head: str) -> str:
    """Rewrite every VS Code-relative code link in prose to a blob permalink.

    Code links are authored one way everywhere — ](./path#start), the same
    grammar a ### heading carries — navigable in the local checkout; but prose
    and the body post to GitHub verbatim, where a relative link resolves to
    nothing, so each is converted here at post time (only the posted copy;
    REVIEW.md on disk keeps its relative links). The #start fragment is the start
    line; a trailing -L<end> in the link TEXT extends it to a range, otherwise
    the permalink is single-line. A fragmentless target names the whole file and
    yields a fragmentless permalink. Absolute links (a curator-pasted permalink)
    start with a scheme, not ./, so they pass through untouched.

    Assumes a lint-clean tree: pr_review_lint.check_fragments has already refused
    any fragment that is not a bare line, so every #frag reached here is digits."""
    def repl(m: "re.Match[str]") -> str:
        link_text, target = m.group(1), m.group(2)
        if "#" in target:
            path, _, frag = target.rpartition("#")
            start: int | None = int(frag)
            em = TEXT_END_L.search(link_text)
            end = int(em.group(1)) if em else start
        else:
            path, start, end = target, None, None
        return f"[{link_text}]({permalink(nwo, head, path, start, end)})"
    return PROSE_LINK.sub(repl, text)


def route(sections: list[Section], nwo: str, head: str
          ) -> tuple[list[dict], list[tuple[str, str, list[str]]]]:
    """Sort checked findings into inline comments and body-folded groups.

    Assumes a lint-clean tree (pr_review_lint.lint has passed): every inline
    anchor is in the diff, no checked finding sits past the third section, and
    every contributing section is labeled — so this only builds, never judges.
    Returns (comments, fold_groups) where a fold group is
    (label, preamble, [rendered finding text...]) in file order.
    """
    comments: list[dict] = []
    fold_groups: list[tuple[str, str, list[str]]] = []

    for s in sections:
        if s.ordinal > 3:  # lint-guaranteed to carry no checked finding
            continue
        items: list[str] = []
        for b in s.blocks:
            if not b.checked:
                continue
            prose = linkify_prose(b.prose, nwo, head)

            # Sections 1 & 2, located: inline. lint has confirmed both endpoints
            # are in the diff, so the all-or-nothing post cannot 422 here.
            if b.located and s.ordinal in (1, 2):
                comment = {"path": b.path, "body": prose,
                           "line": b.end, "side": "RIGHT"}
                if b.end > b.start:
                    comment["start_line"] = b.start
                    comment["start_side"] = "RIGHT"
                comments.append(comment)
                continue

            # Everything else folds: section 3 (any), sections 1 & 2 locationless.
            if b.located:
                base = b.path.rsplit("/", 1)[-1]
                rng = f"L{b.start}" + (f"-L{b.end}" if b.end > b.start else "")
                link = permalink(nwo, head, b.path, b.start, b.end)
                items.append(f"[{base} {rng}]({link})\n\n{prose}")
            else:
                items.append(prose)

        if items:
            # The preamble folds into the body ahead of the group, so its links
            # convert too (only when the section actually contributes).
            fold_groups.append((s.label, linkify_prose(s.preamble, nwo, head), items))

    return comments, fold_groups


def assemble_body(body: str, fold_groups: list[tuple[str, str, list[str]]]) -> str:
    """The PR-level comment: the curated body (status table and any coverage
    caveat), then each contributing section under its label, with its preamble
    copied verbatim, then its findings."""
    parts: list[str] = []
    if body:
        parts.append(body)
    if fold_groups:
        parts.append("---")
        for label, preamble, items in fold_groups:
            parts.append(f"**{label}**")
            if preamble:
                parts.append(preamble)
            parts.extend(items)
    return ("\n\n".join(parts)).strip() + "\n"


def format_recap(sections: list[Section], comments: list[dict], fold_count: int,
                 event: str, imported: list[dict], has_draft: bool) -> str:
    """Human-readable curation recap printed before the prompt: per-section
    checked/unchecked/total, the pending-review import when there is one, then
    the verdict about to be posted. A section that shows 0 checked is the cue
    for a REVIEW.md that was never read to the end."""
    lines = [f"{PROG}: REVIEW.md recap"]
    width = max((len(s.label) for s in sections), default=0)
    for s in sections:
        total = len(s.blocks)
        checked = sum(1 for b in s.blocks if b.checked)
        lines.append(f"  §{s.ordinal} {s.label:<{width}}  checked {checked}"
                     f" / unchecked {total - checked} / total {total}")
    if imported:
        paths = ", ".join(sorted({c["path"] for c in imported}))
        lines.append(f"  + pending review: {len(imported)} comment(s) to import — {paths}")
    if has_draft:
        lines.append("  + pending review: draft body appended to the review body")
    if event == "APPROVE":
        lines.append("  → verdict: APPROVE (no findings checked)")
    else:
        detail = f"{len(comments)} inline, {fold_count} folded"
        if imported:
            detail += f", {len(imported)} imported"
        lines.append("  → verdict: REQUEST_CHANGES "
                     f"({len(comments) + fold_count + len(imported)} finding(s): "
                     f"{detail})")
    return "\n".join(lines) + "\n"


# --- the curator's pending review -----------------------------------------------

def fetch_pending_review(nwo: str, pr_id: str) -> tuple[dict | None, list[dict]]:
    """The curator's own pending review on the PR, with its comments, verbatim.

    GitHub shows a pending review only to its author and allows one per user
    per PR, so at most one is visible here — and while it exists, the finalize
    POST is rejected with 422 even with an event supplied. Read-only: anything
    destructive happens later, after the confirmations."""
    reviews = gh_api_list(f"repos/{nwo}/pulls/{pr_id}/reviews",
                          what=f"listing PR #{pr_id} reviews")
    pending = [r for r in reviews if r.get("state") == "PENDING"]
    if not pending:
        return None, []
    if len(pending) > 1:
        die(f"PR #{pr_id} shows {len(pending)} pending reviews; GitHub allows one "
            "per user and shows only your own, so this should be impossible. "
            "Resolve them on github.com, then re-run.")
    review = pending[0]
    comments = gh_api_list(f"repos/{nwo}/pulls/{pr_id}/reviews/{review['id']}/comments",
                           what="fetching the pending review's comments")
    return review, comments


def convert_pending_comments(comments: list[dict], pr_url: str) -> list[dict]:
    """Pending comments as create-review payload entries, anchors untouched.

    LEFT-side and multi-line anchors pass through: GitHub anchored them to the
    diff by construction, so they need no in-diff lint (and REVIEW.md's grammar
    could not even carry them). Two shapes cannot travel in a create-review
    payload and are refused by name: replies (the payload cannot express
    in_reply_to, and posting them separately after the review would break the
    all-or-nothing post) and file-level comments (no line anchor; payload
    support unconfirmed). A line comment with no line anchor is a stale anchor
    and is refused likewise."""
    imported: list[dict] = []
    refused: list[str] = []
    for c in comments:
        where = f"{c.get('path', '?')}:{c.get('line') or c.get('original_line') or '?'}"
        if c.get("in_reply_to_id"):
            refused.append(f"{where} — a reply to an existing thread")
        elif c.get("subject_type") == "file":
            refused.append(f"{c.get('path', '?')} — a file-level comment")
        elif c.get("line") is None:
            refused.append(f"{where} — no line anchor (stale?)")
        else:
            entry = {"path": c["path"], "body": c["body"],
                     "line": c["line"], "side": c.get("side") or "RIGHT"}
            if c.get("start_line") is not None:
                entry["start_line"] = c["start_line"]
                entry["start_side"] = c.get("start_side") or entry["side"]
            imported.append(entry)
    if refused:
        listing = "\n".join(f"  - {r}" for r in refused)
        die("your pending review carries comment(s) that cannot travel in the "
            f"single review object:\n{listing}\n"
            f"Handle these in the GitHub UI ({pr_url}) — submit or discard the "
            "pending review there — then re-run.")
    return imported


# --- the interactive confirmation ---------------------------------------------

def confirm(prompt: str) -> bool:
    # Prefer the controlling terminal: an irreversible POST should need a real
    # keystroke, not something a pipe or heredoc (`echo y | pr-finalize`) can
    # pre-answer. Two one-directional handles, NOT "r+": any read+write mode builds
    # a BufferedRandom, whose constructor demands a seekable raw stream — and a tty
    # is not seekable, so "r+" raises io.UnsupportedOperation (a subclass of OSError,
    # which silently mislabels the failure as "no terminal"; observed on WSL2).
    try:
        tty_in = open("/dev/tty", "r")
        tty_out = open("/dev/tty", "w")
    except OSError:
        # No controlling terminal (e.g. launched through a wrapper that dropped it).
        # Fall back to stdin, but only if it is itself interactive.
        if not sys.stdin.isatty():
            die("posting is irreversible and needs an interactive terminal to confirm. "
                "Run pr-finalize from a shell, or use --dry-run to preview.")
        sys.stderr.write(prompt)
        sys.stderr.flush()
        return sys.stdin.readline().strip()[:1] in ("y", "Y")
    try:
        tty_out.write(prompt)
        tty_out.flush()
        answer = tty_in.readline().strip()
    finally:
        tty_in.close()
        tty_out.close()
    return answer[:1] in ("y", "Y")


# --- main ---------------------------------------------------------------------

def main(argv: list[str]) -> int:
    dry_run = False
    for arg in argv:
        if arg == "--dry-run":
            dry_run = True
        else:
            die(f"unexpected argument: {arg} (usage: pr-finalize [--dry-run])")

    if shutil.which("gh") is None:
        die("GitHub CLI (gh) is not installed. Install it "
            "(https://github.com/cli/cli#installation), then try again.")

    # Repo root: REVIEW.md and the snapshot live here.
    top = git("rev-parse", "--show-toplevel", what="locating the repository")
    if Path(top).resolve() != Path.cwd().resolve():
        die(f"run pr-finalize from the repository root: {top}")

    if not STATE_DIR.joinpath("state.json").is_file():
        die(f"no preparation snapshot ({STATE_DIR/'state.json'}). "
            "Prepare and review first: pr-review <id>.")
    try:
        state = json.loads(STATE_DIR.joinpath("state.json").read_text())
    except (OSError, ValueError) as e:
        die(f"could not read the preparation snapshot: {e}")
    pr_id = str(state.get("prId", "")).strip()
    head = str(state.get("head", "")).strip()
    if not pr_id.isdigit():
        die("state.json has no usable prId — the snapshot is broken. Re-prepare.")
    if not head:
        die("state.json has no head — the snapshot is broken. Re-prepare.")

    branch = git("rev-parse", "--abbrev-ref", "HEAD", what="reading the branch")
    if branch != f"pr/{pr_id}":
        die(f"not on the prepared branch (HEAD is '{branch}', expected 'pr/{pr_id}'). "
            f"Check it out, or re-prepare: pr-review {pr_id}.")

    if not REVIEW.is_file():
        die("no REVIEW.md at the repo root — nothing curated to post. "
            f"Run the review first: pr-review {pr_id}.")

    # Terminal-state guard: a posted marker closes this preparation.
    if POSTED_MD.exists():
        die(f"PR #{pr_id} was already finalized ({POSTED_MD}). REVIEW.md is kept for "
            f"follow-up; to post again, re-prepare (pr-review {pr_id}) — a fresh "
            "preparation of the current head.")

    # gh signed in (clearer than letting the first API call fail).
    if _run("gh", "auth", "status").returncode != 0:
        die("gh is installed but not signed in. Run 'gh auth login', then try again.")

    # Resolve the repo and print the PR's URL first thing — so it can be opened in
    # a browser (ctrl-click) while the slower live-head check, parsing and routing
    # below run. This needs only the repo name, already in hand from the snapshot's
    # pr_id plus gh's default repo.
    nwo = gh("repo", "view", "--json", "nameWithOwner", "--jq", ".nameWithOwner",
             what="resolving the repository").strip()
    if not nwo:
        die("gh returned no repository name; is a default repo set?")
    print(f"{PROG}: PR #{pr_id} — https://github.com/{nwo}/pull/{pr_id}", file=sys.stderr)

    # Live head check: the reviewed head must still be the PR head, or every line
    # number and permalink the review wrote points at the wrong code.
    live_head = gh("pr", "view", pr_id, "--json", "headRefOid", "--jq", ".headRefOid",
                   what=f"reading PR #{pr_id} head").strip()
    if live_head != head:
        die(f"PR #{pr_id} moved since preparation (GitHub head {live_head[:12]}, "
            f"reviewed head {head[:12]}). The review's anchors no longer match. "
            f"Re-prepare and re-review: pr-review {pr_id}.")

    # The curator's own pending review (GitHub's "Start a review" flow) blocks
    # the POST below — one pending review per user per PR — so detect it now
    # and fold it in, rather than 422 later. Fetch and persist here (fresh
    # every run: comments edited on github.com between runs are picked up);
    # delete only after the confirmations.
    pr_url = f"https://github.com/{nwo}/pull/{pr_id}"
    pending, pending_comments = fetch_pending_review(nwo, pr_id)
    imported: list[dict] = []
    draft_body = ""
    if pending is not None:
        imported = convert_pending_comments(pending_comments, pr_url)
        draft_body = (pending.get("body") or "").strip()
        # Persist the fetched pending review verbatim before anything else —
        # a recovery artifact, never an input. Overwritten on each run (dry
        # runs included: it is handy for debugging); if the POST fails after
        # the delete below, this file is the only surviving copy.
        RUN_DIR.mkdir(exist_ok=True)
        try:
            PENDING_IMPORT.write_text(json.dumps(
                {"review": pending, "comments": pending_comments},
                ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))
        except OSError as e:
            die(f"could not persist the pending review to {PENDING_IMPORT}: {e}. "
                "Nothing was posted or deleted.")

    ranges_path = STATE_DIR / "canonical.diff"
    ranges = parse_diff_ranges(ranges_path.read_text()) if ranges_path.is_file() else {}

    # Parse, then lint the whole file into one batch and report it in file order
    # before building or posting anything: parse_review and the lint pass in
    # pr_review_lint collect every fault, so a curator sees every misfiled
    # finding, unlabeled section and malformed link at once rather than one
    # re-run per fault. Runs after the live-head check above, so no line number
    # it reports is stale; routing below may then assume a valid tree.
    problems: list[Problem] = []
    body, body_line, sections = parse_review(REVIEW.read_text(), problems)
    lint(body, body_line, sections, ranges, problems)
    bail_on_problems(problems, PROG, "nothing posted")

    body = linkify_prose(body, nwo, head)  # lint-clean now: the body always posts
    comments, fold_groups = route(sections, nwo, head)

    body_text = assemble_body(body, fold_groups)
    fold_count = sum(len(items) for _, _, items in fold_groups)

    # The pending review's draft body (summary text typed but not submitted)
    # rides along at the end of the assembled body, separated by ---.
    if draft_body:
        stripped = body_text.strip()
        body_text = (f"{stripped}\n\n---\n\n{draft_body}\n" if stripped
                     else f"{draft_body}\n")

    # Verdict by curation: any checked finding (in any section) blocks; none
    # approves. The checkbox is the blocking signal, not the section — and an
    # imported pending comment is a human-authored finding, checked by the act
    # of writing it, so it blocks too.
    event = "REQUEST_CHANGES" if (comments or fold_count or imported) else "APPROVE"

    # An empty body is fine. GitHub requires a REQUEST_CHANGES review to carry
    # a body OR comments (verified empirically; the docs' "body is required"
    # wording overstates it), and REQUEST_CHANGES here implies comments,
    # fold_count, or imported — and any folded finding makes the body
    # non-empty — so every request this sends is legal by construction.
    payload = {"body": body_text, "event": event, "comments": comments + imported}
    recap = format_recap(sections, comments, fold_count, event, imported,
                         bool(draft_body))

    if dry_run:
        print(json.dumps(payload, indent=2, ensure_ascii=False))
        sys.stderr.write(recap)
        if pending is not None:
            print(f"{PROG}: a pending review of yours exists on PR #{pr_id}; "
                  "finalizing will fold it in as shown and delete it from GitHub "
                  f"(fetched copy: {PENDING_IMPORT}).", file=sys.stderr)
        print(f"{PROG}: dry run — nothing posted.", file=sys.stderr)
        return 0

    sys.stderr.write(recap)

    # The import gate. There is no "post without importing": the POST cannot
    # succeed while the pending review exists, so the choices are import or
    # abort (and the escape hatch is the GitHub UI).
    if pending is not None:
        detail = [f"{len(imported)} comment(s)"] if imported else []
        if draft_body:
            detail.append("a draft body")
        if detail:
            prompt = (f"{PROG}: fold your pending review ({' and '.join(detail)}) "
                      "into this post and delete it from GitHub? [y/N] ")
        else:
            prompt = (f"{PROG}: your pending review is empty but still blocks "
                      "posting; delete it from GitHub and continue? [y/N] ")
        if not confirm(prompt):
            die("declined. Nothing posted, nothing deleted; the pending review is "
                "untouched. To post without importing it, submit or discard it on "
                f"{pr_url}, then re-run.")

    if event == "APPROVE":
        # No findings checked. That can mean "read it, it's clean" — or "never
        # finished reading it". Two gates, the second naming that risk, before an
        # approval that cannot be taken back.
        if not confirm(f"{PROG}: post an APPROVE review to PR #{pr_id} — "
                       "no findings checked? [y/N] "):
            die("declined. Nothing posted; REVIEW.md untouched.")
        if not confirm(f"{PROG}: an unmodified REVIEW.md may simply be unread — "
                       f"confirm you have read it through and PR #{pr_id} is good "
                       "to approve? [y/N] "):
            die("declined. Nothing posted; REVIEW.md untouched.")
    else:
        counts = f"{len(comments)} inline comment(s), {fold_count} finding(s) folded into the body"
        if imported:
            counts += f", {len(imported)} imported comment(s)"
        if not confirm(f"{PROG}: post a REQUEST_CHANGES review to PR #{pr_id} — "
                       f"{counts}? [y/N] "):
            die("declined. Nothing posted; REVIEW.md untouched.")

    # The pending review must go first or the POST is rejected — this is the
    # one destructive step before the post, and pending-import.json already
    # holds a verbatim copy. A failed DELETE dies here with nothing lost.
    if pending is not None:
        gh("api", "--method", "DELETE",
           f"repos/{nwo}/pulls/{pr_id}/reviews/{pending['id']}",
           what="deleting the pending review")

    # Post one review object. The base repo (nwo) holds the PR and its diff; for
    # an open PR the head commit is reachable there, fork or not. Not the gh()
    # helper: past the DELETE above a failure must point at the recovery copy.
    recovery = ("" if pending is None else
                " Your pending review was already deleted from GitHub; its "
                f"fetched copy survives in {PENDING_IMPORT}.")
    p = _run("gh", "api", "--method", "POST",
             f"repos/{nwo}/pulls/{pr_id}/reviews", "--input", "-",
             stdin=json.dumps(payload))
    if p.returncode != 0:
        die(f"posting the review failed: {p.stderr.strip() or 'gh error'}."
            f"{recovery}")
    response_text = p.stdout
    try:
        response = json.loads(response_text)
        review_url = response.get("html_url", "")
    except ValueError:
        review_url = ""
    if not review_url:
        die("the POST returned no review URL — treating it as a failure."
            f"{recovery} Response:\n{response_text}")

    # Archive AND mark, marker first: posted.md is both the as-posted snapshot and
    # the guard, so writing it first closes the double-post window as early as
    # possible. A failure after a successful post is reported loudly.
    RUN_DIR.mkdir(exist_ok=True)
    try:
        shutil.copyfile(REVIEW, POSTED_MD)
    except OSError as e:
        print(f"{PROG}: POSTED OK ({review_url}) but could not write the marker "
              f"{POSTED_MD}: {e}. The review is live; do NOT re-run — create "
              f"{POSTED_MD} by hand to lock it.", file=sys.stderr)
        return 1
    try:
        POSTED_JSON.write_text(json.dumps({"payload": payload, "response": response},
                                          ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))
    except OSError as e:
        print(f"{PROG}: warning — posted.json not written ({e}), but the posted.md "
              f"marker is set (no double-post risk). Review: {review_url}",
              file=sys.stderr)

    print(f"{PROG}: posted: {review_url}", file=sys.stderr)
    print(f"{PROG}: REVIEW.md kept at the repo root — unchecked findings survive for "
          f"a follow-up. This preparation is finalized; re-prepare (pr-review {pr_id}) "
          "to start over.", file=sys.stderr)
    return 0


if __name__ == "__main__":
    raise SystemExit(main(sys.argv[1:]))
